  ${
    $d x y z A $.  $d x y z F $.  $d x y z M $.  $d z R $.
    abvmet.a $e |- A = ( AbsVal ` R ) $.
    abvmet.m $e |- M = ( -g ` R ) $.
    $( An absolute value ` F ` generates a metric defined by
       ` d ( x , y ) = F ( x - y ) ` , analogously to ~ cnmet .  (In fact, the
       ring structure is not needed at all; the group properties ~ abveq0 and
       ~ abvtri , ~ abvneg are sufficient.)  (Contributed by Mario Carneiro,
       9-Sep-2014.) $)
    abvmet $p |- ( F e. A -> ( F o. M ) e. Met ) $=
      ( vx vy wcel cr co wceq wb wa cvv cfv eqid syl syl3anc df-ov ccom cme cdm
      vz cxp wf cv cc0 caddc cle wbr wral csg fvex eqeltri coexg mpan2 cbs abvf
      ismet cgrp crg abvrcl rnggrp grpsubf fco syl2anc fdm dmeqd dmxpid xpeq12d
      syl6eq feq2d mpbird eleq2d anbi12d biimpa c0g cop wfun adantr ffun adantl
      opelxpi fvco3 fveq2i 3eqtr4g eqeq1d grpsubcl 3expb sylan abveq0 grpsubeq0
      syldan 3bitrd cplusg simpl simprll simprr simprlr abvtri adantrr syl13anc
      grpaddsubass oveq1d eqtr3d fveq2d eqtr4d cminusg abvneg grpsubinv 3eqtr2d
      grpnpcan oveq12d 3brtr4d expr sylbid ralrimiv jca ralrimivva mpbir2and )
